            <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-container">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <div class="faq-question">
                        <span>Is this service really free to use?</span>
                        <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <p>Yes, our image compression tool is completely free to use with no hidden charges or watermarks on your images.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <div class="faq-question">
                        <span>What is the maximum file size I can compress?</span>
                        <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <p>You can compress images up to 10MB in size. For larger files, we recommend resizing them first before compression.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <div class="faq-question">
                        <span>Will compressing my image reduce its quality?</span>
                        <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <p>Some quality reduction is inevitable with lossy formats like JPG, but our tool finds the optimal balance between file size and visual quality. For lossless compression, choose PNG format.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <div class="faq-question">
                        <span>Which format should I choose for the best compression?</span>
                        <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <p>WebP generally offers the best compression with good quality. For maximum compatibility, JPG is still the best choice. PNG is recommended when you need lossless quality.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
